<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ910208-0153</DOCNO><DOCID>910208-0153.</DOCID><HL>   Giddings andamp; Lewis Inc.   To Post Profit Rise   For Fourth Quarter</HL><DATE>02/08/91</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION</SO><CO>   GIDL</CO><IN>DOW JONES INTERVIEW (CEO)FACTORY EQUIPMENT (FAC)</IN><LP>   FOND DU LAC, Wis. -- Spurred by continued strong demandfor its machine tools, Giddings andamp; Lewis Inc. expects toreport Friday a rise between 13% and 18% in fourth-quarterearnings.   Richard C. Kleinfeldt, chief financial officer, said in areport that the company expects to post profit of $5.1million to $5.3 million, or 48 cents to 50 cents a share.That would be up from $4.5 million, or 43 cents a share, ayear earlier.</LP><TEXT>   Included in the latest results, Mr. Kleinfeldt said, willbe an extraordinary benefit of about $300,000, or two tothree cents a share. That's from using foreign net operatingloss carry-forwards from the company's subsidiary inScotland.   The company said it expects to report a 17% rise in salesfor the quarter to about $66 million from $56.5 million ayear earlier.   In addition, Giddings andamp; Lewis said its year-end backlogjumped to about $185 million from $152 million at the end of1989.   Although he didn't make projections for 1991, Mr.Kleinfeldt said Giddings andamp; Lewis is optimistic it will beable to &quot;achieve further gains in both sales and earnings.&quot;   Company officials said that despite the recession, manycustomers are intent on making their factories moreefficient, resulting in new orders for the factory equipmentthat Giddings andamp; Lewis makes. The company said business wasespecially strong for its Gilman Assembly Automation unit,which makes automated assembly systems.   William J. Fife Jr., chairman and chief executive, saidthat with the conflict in the Mideast, orders from thedefense and oil industries have picked up in recent months.   With the decline in the dollar making U.S. goods lessexpensive to customers abroad, Mr. Fife said Europe will bean important market for the company this year.   Mr. Fife said the countries of eastern and western Europeaccount for about half of the machine tools purchased in theworld. He said the company set up a sales office in Belgiumlast year to help penetrate those markets.   Giddings andamp; Lewis also plans to continue investing in itsown factories, with some $20 million in capital spendingslated for 1991, up from about $14 million in 1990, and $6.5million in 1989.   The company continues to conservatively manage its balancesheet. Mr. Kleinfeldt said it showed no debt at the end of1990, and that cash had grown to more than $20 million.That's up from $10.7 million at the end of 1989 and $1.3million at the end of 1988.</TEXT></DOC>